          <text>
            Day two starts like day one: bioluminescence brightening, Scout bouncing a good morning, Holloway's fruiting body emerging for the daily wellness check.

            Holloway asks, "Good morning, Kira! How would you rate your overall wellness today?"

            I say, "Eight. Wound healing well, pain minimal, sleep quality good."

            See, I'm learning—efficient answers in their language make everything faster.

            Holloway asks, "Any new symptoms or concerns?"

            I say, "None. Ready for wound care assessment."

            Holloway says, "Perfect! I'm documenting your progress. Remedy will be here shortly."

            The routine is becoming automatic—almost comfortable.

            By day three I can recite the wellness check from memory: eight out of ten, wound closure improving, no concerns. The mushroom-paste meals are not good exactly, but familiar—three times daily, nutritionally complete. They taste like defeat mixed with earth, but my body recognizes them as food now. That's something.

            Scout stays close, a constant companion through every form and meal. The little plant has become my anchor—a non-verbal presence that somehow helps more than words.

            I ask Buddy between bites of grayish lunch, "How many days until Elder Heartwood might respond?"

            Buddy replies, "Based on Holloway's estimate of eight to twelve weeks, accounting for the one week elapsed—fifty-five to eighty-three days remaining. _Approximately_."

            Fifty-five days minimum—that's a lot of wellness checks, a lot of mushroom paste, a lot of counting ceiling patterns in my quarters while waiting for something to happen.

            ¶

            Day four. Morning wellness check complete in under three minutes—new record. I'm getting _good_ at this: answer efficiently, use their frameworks, provide requested documentation. The bureaucratic language is becoming second nature.

            Holloway says warmly, "Your adaptation has been remarkable! We're very pleased with your integration progress."

            _Integration_—like I'm joining their community instead of being stranded with no options.

            But… aren't I, though? I'm adapting successfully—efficiently, even. And it's incredibly boring.

            Day five passes in a blur of routine: wellness check nine out of ten, wound nearly healed; breakfast of mushroom paste with extra protein compound; mid-day sitting in my quarters watching bioluminescent patterns shift; dinner more mushroom paste; evening lying awake counting the days. Fifty-two more days minimum.

            Day six begins the same: wellness check, wound care—Remedy declares it healing beautifully with new tissue forming perfectly—meals, forms, more meals.

            Buddy says during lunch, "Kira, I'm detecting elevated restlessness markers—would you like some suggestions for constructive activities to occupy your time?"
          </text>
