        <chunk>
          <text>
            I ask Buddy:
            "Like what?"
            Buddy replies:
            "Learning the local plant communication protocols more thoroughly! Exploring the facility's architectural features! Documenting your experiences for future reference!"
            All things I could do—should do, probably—but none of them feel like progress; they feel like _waiting_.
            I'm good at a lot of things—adapting, apparently; surviving; working within impossible systems through sheer stubborn determination. Patience is not on that list.
            Scout rolls closer and bumps gently against my leg—comfort. They seem to sense my mood shifting.
            I tell Scout:
            "I'm okay—just... thinking."
            Day seven—one week since filing the Elder Heartwood query. Fifty-one to seventy-seven days remaining.
            Morning wellness check goes perfectly—efficiency at its finest. Ten out of ten, wound fully closed, ready to remove bandaging entirely. Remedy is pleased. Holloway documents everything meticulously. I provide all requested information without prompting.
            I've mastered bureaucratic plant life, and I still have nearly two months of it ahead of me—minimum.
            I appreciate them—really, truly do. But appreciation doesn't make waiting easier.
            I sit in my quarters after lunch, Scout settled nearby, and try to think strategically. Waiting sucks, but it's the plan. Elder Heartwood will respond eventually—guidance will come. I just need to be patient.
            Except patience feels passive. Sitting here eating mushroom paste and rating my wellness while weeks crawl by—that's not who I am. I fix things. Find solutions. Take action.
            I say to Buddy:
            "Buddy— the Elder Heartwood query... we're waiting for them to respond through communication channels, right? Through the network?"
            Buddy replies:
            "Correct! Holloway filed formal query documentation for network relay transmission to Elder Heartwood's grove. Response will return through same channels."
            I ask Buddy:
            "But Elder is... an actual being, in an actual location, right?"
            I call to the walls; a fruiting body sprouts near the entrance within seconds. Holloway asks:
            "Yes, Kira? Do you need something?"
            I ask Holloway:
            "Question about Elder Heartwood—you said they're distant, and communication takes time because of relay systems and their slow processing pace."
            Holloway replies:
            "That's correct! Elder Heartwood exists in deep time. Responses require patience."
            I ask Holloway:
            "Right—but they're... somewhere, right? Like, geographically somewhere?"
          </text>
