        <chunk>
          <text>
            A brief pause—fruiting bodies consult with each other.

            The fruiting bodies say:
            "Yes. Elder Heartwood resides in the Ancient Grove, several network territories from here. Why do you ask?"

            My heart rate picks up—Scout bounces, sensing the energy shift.

            I say:
            "How far? Exactly?"

            The fruiting bodies say:
            "Quite distant. Through multiple territorial boundaries, across different network jurisdictions." More fruiting body consultation. "The journey would take… perhaps two to three weeks? Traveling through connected networks. It's not common for individuals to make such journeys—communication relay is more efficient for most purposes."

            «Two to three weeks».

            ¶

            Versus fifty-plus days of waiting.

            I say carefully:
            "Wait—are you saying I could… travel there? To Elder Heartwood's grove? Instead of waiting for communication relay?"

            Holloway replies:
            "Technically, yes. Though it would require formal travel permissions, territorial coordination, guide assignments… It's not typically how we handle queries. Most beings prefer to wait for responses rather than undertake such journeys."

            Most beings probably have more patience than I do.

            Two to three weeks of traveling—doing something, making progress, actively working toward the goal—versus two to three months of sitting here eating mushroom paste and counting ceiling patterns.

            I say:
            "Tell me more about this journey—how does it work? What would I need?"

            Scout bounces enthusiastically—seeming to approve of this line of questioning.

            Holloway replies:
            "Well, it would require filing a formal travel request. Requesting assigned guides familiar with the route and various network territories. Securing permissions from each jurisdiction along the way. Coordinating with Elder Heartwood's grove to ensure appropriate arrival protocols…"

            More bureaucracy—obviously.

            But bureaucracy with «purpose».

            I stand up—energy returning for the first time in days—Scout bounces higher, matching my mood.

            I say:
            "Let's talk about this travel request—tell me everything I'd need to do."

            Because I'm done waiting.

            *Time to move.*
          </text>
